column49: Hi, I’ve noticed a lot of changes to the website and I’m pretty disappointed to see a lot of things have disappeared since last year. There are no more classroom packs that I can find, where we could buy 5 or 10 copies of the same book, so that I could have enough for each child to read. I also am disappointed to see that you got rid of the teacher dollar store. I know that a lot of my parents have also asked when you will start doing the $1 book of the week again. We have definitely lost parent interest with the prices of books being higher than it was previously. It no longer feels like it’s a deal to buy from scholastic. I hope that these changes aren’t permanent.

column49: The search function is terrible - it gives imprecise results and sometimes leaves out results that should be included. I've been ordering for three years and the site never fails to frustrate.    Also frustrating is the lack of detail in the book descriptions. This is particularly egregious with packs of books. There is almost never a list of titles that are included or their number in a series. This means that you can't be sure you're not ordering duplicates without looking at each book cover in a pack and trying to compare to what you already have. A prime example is the Bad Guys series. In one pack, books #1-10 were included. Then, I went to buy the next set and tried to compare covers because no numbers are on the covers. I apparently wasn't careful enough and the next set was books #9-16. A simple list of the books included plus their number in the series would have resolved this, but so would not duplicating books in packs. This all seems very basic, so it's incredibly irritating

column49: I HATE the new systems and process for Scholastic book ordering.   I have been a committed Scholastic Teacher for 26 years and I'm VERY close to walking away.   Your products are cheaply made, your flyers are terrible and not conducive to classroom use and honestly I feel like you always have the same titles... I'm always looking for new things for my students and I'm tired of seeing the same options over and over again.   There are very poor rewards, all to no incentives for teachers to give any time or effort to supporting Scholastic any longer.   This is one way to get Scholastic to end their long and amazing run as classrooms' primary source of new books.

column49: I have ordered from Scholastic for over 30 years.  The cost of books has risen so much that it is not affordable for many families--actually most of my students' families.  The quality of books has also decreased.  Scholastic used to offer quality literature.  It is where I purchased most of the books for my classroom library in addition to my own children's books in addition to gifts.  Now it seems Scholastic offers mostly "fad" books--Paw Patrol, Hot Wheels, Gabby's Dollhouse, etc...  Children need exposure to good, quality literature.  Plus your website is so confusing to navigate.  It used to be extremely easy to place orders.  I do not order near as frequently as I used to and honestly have considered giving up Scholastic all together.  I am sorry to write such a negative review, however I hope that it will be read and considered as I would like to continue business with Scholastic.

column38: Other, order books for Christmas gifts for my classrooms
column49: I am very disappointed with Scholastic this year. We did not receive our first set of flyers until after school started, then received our October flyers within a couple weeks after we received Septembers and have not received any since.  Our biggest orders have always been September and November, and this year, no one placed a November order because they never had a flyer. When I called in September asking about our flyers, the women I spoke to said the parents can order online. Sure they can, but it has been proven that we get bigger orders with flyers. I rely on parent orders to purchase gifts and items for our classroom. This year has been awful as far as earning points. Not to mention, in September, when I placed an order, I was supposed to get (a whopping 10.00 to spend) and I never received that. :(

column49: I do not like the new version of Scholastic. I liked sending home the paper flyers, including my code and due date. I do not like not being able to set my own due date....oftentimes the one set by Scholastic does not coincide with our schedule. I always sent book orders home at the beginning of the month with our classroom calendar...and I already feel like it gets sent home just "whenever". I have seen a significant decrease in orders already, and it's only November. Families liked to look through fliers with their preschooler, and then order from there. Browsing the site, even as a teacher, is confusing and not simple and straight forward.

column49: I used to love Scholastic. After that brief time when it took a very long time to receive books a couple years back, things have changed. My 2 biggest frustrations are that books with CDs for listening centers no longer appear to be sold and that there seem to be fewer solid nonfiction texts for young readers. I understand that inflation has taken it's toll however, the decreasing frequency of high-interest $1 or $2 books makes it difficult to purchase sets for a small group or class sets for gifts. I do appreciate the coupons after a reasonable price point has been reached that helps a lot!
